04632nam a22007215i 9781442673373DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20172002onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426733737 a10.3138/97814426733732doi  a(DE-B1597)483125  a(OCoLC)1004886725  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aHD8106.5b.W57 2002eb 7aPOL0280002bisacsh04a331.1/09713/0917341 aLeach, Belinda, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aContingent Work, Disrupted Lives :bLabour and Community in the New Rural Economy /cBelinda Leach, Anthony Winson. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2017] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Comparative Political Economy and Public Policy00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tMap -- tChapter One. Introduction -- tChapter Two. The Global and the Local: Understanding Globalization through Community Research -- tChapter Three. Community Sketches, History, and Method -- tChapter Four. The New Rural Economy Shape of Restructuring -- tChapter Five. Skidding into the Contingent Work World -- tChapter Six. ‘Forget All Your Dreams and Good Luck with Your Life’: Lay-Off and the New Reality of Contingent Labour -- tChapter Seven. Economic Diversity, Sustainability, and Manufacturing Communities -- tChapter Eight. Some Concluding Thoughts -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aContingent Work, Disrupted Lives examines the repercussions of economic globalization on several manufacturing-dependent rural communities in Canada. Foregrounding a distinct interest in the 'grassroots' effects of such contemporary corporate strategies as plant closures and downsizing, authors Anthony Winson and Belinda Leach consider the impact of this restructuring on the residents of various communities. The authors argue that the new rural economy involves a fundamental shift in the stability and security of people's lives and, ultimately, it causes wrenching change and an arduous struggle as rural dwellers struggle to rebuild their lives in the new economic terrain. Beginning with broader theoretical and empirical literature on global changes in the economy and the effects of these changes on labour, the text then focuses exploration on manufacturing in Ontario with an analysis of five community case studies. Winson and Leach give considerable attention to the testimony of numerous residents; they report on in-depth interviews with key respondents and blue-collar workers in five separate communities, ranging from diverse manufacturing towns to single-industry settlements. The result is an intimate contextual knowledge of the workers' lives and their attempts to adapt to the tumultuous economic terrain of 1990s rural Canada.Winner of the John Porter Prize for 2003, awarded by the Canadian Sociology and Anthropology Association.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aDisplaced workerszOntario. 0aRural industrieszOntario. 0aRural unemploymentzOntario. 0aWorking classzOntario. 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / General.2bisacsh1 aWinson, Anthony, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144267337340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442673373423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442673373.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK